notes.speech: In 1984, Naida Glavish, then a telephone operator, was forbidden to greet callers with "Kia ora". She refused and was demoted. The backlash, by both Māori and Pākehā using the greeting, was significant in the resurgence of spoken Māori. To have her use it here seemed a fitting way to end the North Island recordings.
